# Binary Search in JavaScript: Iterative and Recursive Approaches

Binary search is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that finds elements in sorted arrays with O(log n) time complexity. Here are two implementations:

## Iterative Implementation

```javascript
function binarySearchIterative(arr, target) {
  let left = 0;
  let right = arr.length - 1;

  while (left <= right) {
    // Use bitwise right shift to avoid potential overflow
    // (left + right) could exceed MAX_SAFE_INTEGER in very large arrays
    const mid = left + ((right - left) >> 1);

    if (arr[mid] === target) return mid;

    if (arr[mid] < target) {
      left = mid + 1;
    } else {
      right = mid - 1;
    }
  }

  return -1; // Element not found
}
```

## Recursive Implementation

```javascript
function binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, left = 0, right = arr.length - 1) {
  // Base case: element not found
  if (left > right) return -1;

  const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);

  // Found the target
  if (arr[mid] === target) return mid;

  // Recursive cases
  if (arr[mid] < target) {
    // Search right half
    return binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, mid + 1, right);
  } else {
    // Search left half
    return binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, left, mid - 1);
  }
}
```

## Usage Example

```javascript
const sortedArray = [3, 9, 14, 22, 31, 47, 58, 65, 73, 88, 94];

// Iterative approach
console.log(binarySearchIterative(sortedArray, 31)); // Output: 4

// Recursive approach
console.log(binarySearchRecursive(sortedArray, 31)); // Output: 4

// Element not in array
console.log(binarySearchIterative(sortedArray, 32)); // Output: -1
```

## Time & Space Complexity
- **Time Complexity**: O(log n) - the search space is halved each iteration
- **Space Complexity**: O(1) for iterative, O(log n) for recursive due to call stack

The iterative version is generally preferred for performance, but the recursive version can be more intuitive for some developers.

